@node MAIN "Welcome"
@{b}First Steps to Using The Digital Universe@{ub}



      @{"  Starting The Digital Universe              " link startdu}

      @{"  Proceed to the main Digital Universe Help  " link "/duhelp.guide/MAIN"}


@{b}Getting the best out of Digital Universe on OS4@{ub}

In order for The Digital Universe to look its best and run smoothly it is
best to ensure that MUI is set up correctly and that the Screen that
Digital Universe runs on is set to have a similar GUI and Palette to your
current Workbench.

Graphical glitches can occur if using "Softsprite" mouse pointers so
please DO NOT use the SOFTSPRITE settings for your monitor.


      @{"  Adjusting MUI Windows to use Smart Refresh " link "MUISETTINGS"}

      @{"  Monitor Settings and Softsprites           " link "SOFTSPRITES"}

      @{"  Is this Guide Window too Big ?             " link "GUIDEWINDOW"}

      @{"  Resizing DU's Other Windows                " link "MUISNAPSHOT"}
 
      @{"  Sound and the MPEGA Datatype               " link  "SOUND"}

      @{"  What HELP key ?                            " link  "HELPKEY"}

      @{"  Using the OS4 Screens Prefs Application    " link "SCREENSPREFS"}
 
@endnode

@node SCREENSPREFS "Screens Prefs"
AMIGA OS4 SCREENS PREFS
-----------------------

As "The Digital Universe" will automatically copy your Workbench look and
feel it is not necessary to set up an OS4 Screens Prefs setting for it.

If for some reason your "DigitalUniverse" screen does not inherit your
Workbench colours and GUI then set up a Screens prefs for it as shown below.
Note: It should also be possible for a user to set up a custom GUI for
the "DigitalUniverse" screen if they so desire.

One thing that is important to ensure is that any Default Screens setting
does not over ride DU's ability to select its own screen sizes or ability
to utilise over sized scrollable screens.  To ensure this run the
@{"sys:Prefs/Screens" system "c:run >nil: sys:Prefs/Screens >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"} application as detailed below and for the Default setting
make sure that both Screenmode and Font Apply: cycle gadgets in the
@{fg fill}Display@{fg text} tab are set to "Never". They should default to "Never" as this
is the recommended setting in the OS4 documentation. If they are set
to something else then set them to "Never" now.


================================================================
To enable the Digital Universe screen to use the WB like settings run
@{"sys:Prefs/Screens" system "c:run >nil: sys:Prefs/Screens >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"} (click the link to run the application).

Note: Some OS4 users may have the @{fg fill}Default@{fg text} screen set to use the GUI and
Palette to be "Like Workbench" in which case there is no need to do
anything as DU will inherit the settings anyway.

However, some users, myself included, prefer to leave the Default as is and
set up each screen individually.

To do this, enter the name "Digital Universe" in the @{fg fill}Defined Screens List@{fg text}.
TIP: If Digital Universe is already running then you can just click the
@{fg fill}Insert Open Screen@{fg text} button and the user is presented with a list of currently
open screens.

Ignore the @{fg fill}Display@{fg text} tab completely, we still want DU to be able to
choose what screenmode it uses and DU absolutely requires to use its own font.

However, do make sure that both Screenmode and Font Apply: cycle gadgets are
set to "Never". They should default to "Never" as this is the recommended
setting in the OS4 documentation. If they are set to something else then set
them to "Never" now.

Click the @{fg fill}GUI@{fg text} tab. In the @{fg fill}Settings@{fg text} cycle gadget select @{fg fill}Like Workbench@{fg text},
leave other settings as default.

Click the @{fg fill}Palette@{fg text} tab. In the @{fg fill}Settings@{fg text} cycle gadget select @{fg fill}Like Workbench@{fg text},
leave other settings as default.
Do not lock any colours or the night palette feature of DU may be compromised.


Once finished click @{fg fill}Save@{fg text}. Next time the Digital Universe screen is opened
the effects will be evident. TIP: If the Digital Universe screen is already
open you will not see any change. Iconify DU and then click the DU appicon to
re-open the screen and show the changes made.

@endnode

@node MUISETTINGS "MUI Settings"
MUI SETTINGS - USING SMART REFRESH WINDOWS
------------------------------------------

The Digital Universe uses the excellent MUI libraries for its GUI. MUI comes
as standard as an OS4 contribution. MUI is highly configurable so feel free
to play around with it to customise your GUI.

It is important that when running Digital Universe to set the Windows used
by MUI to Smart Refresh. There are two reasons for this, moving windows with
Simple Refresh is ugly and jerky. Secondly using Simple Refresh forces a
redraw of the DU background window every time a window is moved or resized.
If using DU's smart object labelling option, the redraw causes objects to
be labelled multiple times. This problem does not occur when using Smart
Refresh.

On older Amigas where memory, especially chip emory was in short supply, MUI
users would often set the window behaviour to Simple Refresh. With any Amiga
capable of running OS4 this is not a problem so Smart Refresh should be used
for all MUI applications.

To set the MUI behaviour @{i}globally@{ui} run the application "@{"mui:mui" system "c:run >nil: mui:mui >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}" which
will affect @{i}all@{ui} your MUI applications.

To set the behaviour for @{i}just Digital Universe@{ui}, run Digital Universe and
select the @{fg fill}Settings@{fg text} menu and the @{fg fill}MUI...@{fg text} option.

This will run the @{"MUI Preferences" system "sys:utilities/multiview muiprefs.png"} application. Click the @{fg fill}Windows@{fg text} section
and then change the @{fg fill}Refresh@{fg text} cycle gadget to @{fg fill}Smart@{fg text}.
Finally, click the @{fg fill}Save@{fg text} button.
@endnode


@node GUIDEWINDOW "Resize the Guide Window"
RESIZING THIS GUIDE WINDOW
--------------------------

Resize the window, move it to where you want it to show. Go to the @{fg fill}Prefs@{fg text}
menu and select @{fg fill}Save as Defaults@{fg text}.

Note this is done on a screen by screen basis, so if you do this on the
Workbench screen it will not affect the help files viewed FROM Digital
Universe. When running Digital Universe, press the Help key, most likely
the help window will initially be full screen size. Just size and position
the window and save the settings as above.
@endnode

@node MUISNAPSHOT "Resizing DigitalUniverse MUI Windows"
RESIZING the Windows of The Digital Universe
--------------------------------------------

You are not stuck with the default sizes of any of the windows used in
The Digital Universe. The size and position of any MUI window can be
snapshot to the user's wishes. To do this MUI should be set to have
either the "snapshot" icon or the "drop down menu" icon in the MUI
window titlebars.

To set the MUI behaviour @{i}globally@{ui} run the application "@{"mui:mui" system "c:run >nil: mui:mui >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}" which
will affect @{i}all@{ui} your MUI applications.

To set the behaviour for @{i}just Digital Universe@{ui}, run Digital Universe and
select the @{fg fill}Settings@{fg text} menu and the @{fg fill}MUI...@{fg text} option.

This will run the @{"MUI Preferences" system "sys:utilities/multiview muiprefs.png"} application. Click the @{fg fill}Windows@{fg text} section
and select the gadgets you wish to use.

TIP. To avoid clutter, only the drop down menu is really needed, as this
contains all the options of the other icons in one drop down menu.
Finally, click the @{fg fill}Save@{fg text} button.

@endnode




@node SOFTSPRITES "Monitor Settings and Softsprites"

MONITOR TOOLTYPES
-----------------

Most Amiga OS4 systems will use a hardware sprite for the mouse pointer. It
is possible to set up the OS4 graphics system to use a software sprite
instead. However, using a software sprite causes graphical glitches in
Digital Universe when rendering planets. It is advised to avoid the use of
a software sprite pointer to avoid any graphical glitches in Digital Universe.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NOTE:@{bg back}@{fg text} With some graphics cards, the higher end Radeons, unfortunately
the SOFTSPRITE option had to be set in pre-releases of Amiga OS4 in order to
boot. Note that if using a pre-release of Amiga OS4 update to the final
version where it is perfectly safe to disable SOFTSPRITE with any graphics card.

@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NOTE:@{bg back}@{fg text} Additional information added for the DU v1.6 release.
Users who have upgraded to Amiga OS4.1 will be able to use a SOFTSPRITE pointer
with no adverse effects in The Digital Universe.

To check whether you are using a software sprite or not do the following:

Open the drawer @{"devs:monitors" system "c:rx 'ADDRESS WORKBENCH WINDOW WINDOWS \"devs:monitors\" OPEN' >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"} and you will see the driver currently used for
your current graphics card. Select its icon and choose Info. Check the TOOLTYPES
used for this icon. If there is an entry "SOFTSPRITE=Yes" then either set the
TOOLTYPE to "SOFTSPRITE=No" or put brackets around the TOOLTYPE which will have
the same effect.

@endnode

@node SOUND "Sound and the MPEGA Datatype"
                                        
The INTRO to The Digital Universe plays a theme which in the current release uses
an mp3 file. In order to play this sound, a datatype capable of playing mp3 files
is required and none is supplied as part of Amiga OS4.

If no datatype is found then Digital Universe will still play the Intro but 
without any sound. If you wish to hear the sound a third party datatype will
need to be downloaded.

A suitable datatype can be obtained from OS4 Depot at
@{"http://os4depot.net/share/datatype/sound/mpegadt.lha"  system "c:run >nil: c:openurl http://os4depot.net/share/datatype/sound/mpegadt.lha >con://///AUTO/WAIT/CLOSE"}

Note: If you have OpenURL installed and the file c:openurl exists then clicking
the above link will download the file for you !

@endnode


@node HELPKEY "Help Key and Right AMIGA Key"

If using a PC keyboard rather than an Amiga keyboard there is no key marked HELP
for you to initiate the Help system. Amiga OS4 maps the HELP key to the Scroll
Lock key by default so treat this as your HELP key.

Likewise the Right Amiga key used in menu shortcuts will be mapped to the right
hand side Windows key on a PC keyboard.
@endnode

@node startdu "Starting The Digital Universe"
If you would like to start "The Digital Universe" from the Workbench, you only
have to double click upon the "DigitalUniverse" icon once the software has been
installed.

If you would like to run the software without seeing the introduction, just
enable the NOINTRO tooltype in the "DigitalUniverse" icon.

If you would like to run the software using the @{"sticky windows" link "/duhelp.guide/menu_sticky"} option, just
enable the STICKY tooltype in the "DigitalUniverse" icon.

If you want to enable the "Escape" key to be used to quit "The Digital Universe"
then enable the ESCAPE tooltype in the "DigitalUniverse" icon.


On the other hand, you can also start the software from the command line
(CLI). To do this, change to the DigitalUniverse: directory and type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse@{fg text}

A list of the optional CLI arguments for "The Digital Universe" can be
found by using the ? key. Type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse ?@{fg text}


If you would like to avoid the introduction, type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse nointro@{fg text}  or   @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse ni@{fg text}
If you would like to enable @{"sticky windows", link "/duhelp.guide/menu_sticky"} type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse sticky@{fg text}

If you want to enable the "Escape" key to be used to quit "The Digital Universe"
then type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse escape@{fg text}

One other option is available to CLI users.  If your configuration somehow
becomes corrupted or you would like to return your settings to the factory
defaults, type:

        @{fg fill}DigitalUniverse init@{fg text}

Remember that if you do so, all your previous settings will be lost.

However, using the "init" parameter to reset to the default configuration
will @{b}not@{ub} over-ride your @{"Environment Settings" link /duhelp.guide/window_environ}.


When you run the software for the @{b}first time@{ub}, you will need to tell it
literally "where on the Earth" you are located, and what time zone you are
in. If you have a previous version of "The Digital Universe" copy your old
du.environ file to your current Digital Universe folder.

If no du.environ file is found then "The Digital Universe" will
automatically open the @{"Environment Settings Window" link /duhelp.guide/window_environ} where you can enter
your location details or load a file from a previous version of DU.

At any later time you can alter your Environment by choosing
@{"Environment Prefs" link /duhelp.guide/menu_environ} from the menu bar, to bring up the
@{"Setting Environment Parameters" link /duhelp.guide/window_environ} window.  See the help associated with this
window for more details.

@endnode





